description: a python package that measure the environmental impact of computation provides a function to evaluate the energy usage and related carbon emission of another function emission are calculated based on the user s location via the geojs api and that location s energy mix data source u e i a and egrid for the year to install simply pip install energyusage to evaluate the emission of a function just call energyusage evaluate with the function name and the argument it requires it will return the value of your function while also printing out the energy usage report on the command line optional keyword argument the report that will be printed out will look like the one below the second and third line will show a real time reading that disappears once the process ha finished evaluating the report is divided into several section final reading present an average of energy data the energy mix of the location emission the effective co emission of running the program one time and some real world equivalent to those emission assumed carbon equivalencies the formula used to convert from kwh to co based on the energy mix of the location for international location see below for more information emission comparison what the emission would be for the same energy used in a representative group of u state and country note that if these location are specified a described below these default value are not shown process used the amount of energy running the program used in total the pdf report contains the same section but doe not include the process duration or the emission comparison momentarily we calculate cpu power usage via the rapl running average power limit interface found on intel processor these are non architectural model specific register that provide power related information about the cpu they are used primarily for limiting power consumption but the energy status register msr pkg energy status allows for power measurement the rapl interface differentiates between several domain based on the number of processor for a single processor machine for a machine with multiple processor presently we use the package domain or a sum of all of the domain for a multi processor machine which represents the complete processor package a outlined by vince weaver there are multiple way to access the rapl interface data namely we elected to use the final method because it is the only one that doe not require sudo access we read the energy uj txt file inside the package folder s intel rapl these file represent the energy used in microjoules and they update roughly every millisecond the value in the file increase to the point of overflow and then reset we take reading with a delay in between and then calculate the wattage based on the difference energy and the delay time to avoid error due to the reset of the file we discard negative value for more information on the rapl interface consult the intel and ia architecture software developer s manual to the package measurement we also add the power usage of the gpu for machine that have an nvidia gpu that support the nvidia smi program the nvidia smi is a command line utility that allows for the querying of information about the gpu if the gpu is identified a valid we use the built in method to query the current wattage and then convert the output into a float more information on nvidia smi can be found on the nvidia website in order to accurately calculate the co emission associated with the computational power used we determine the geographical location of the user via their ip address with the help of the geojs api if the location cannot be determined we use the united state a the default location is especially important a the emission differ based on the country s and in the case of the united state the state s energy mix we obtained international energy mix data from the u s energy information administration data for the year specifically we looked at the energy consumption of country worldwide broken down by energy source for the data point labeled s meaning that the value is too small for the number of decimal place shown we approximated those amount to no data wa available for and thus we removed from consideration the following former czechoslovakia former serbia and montenegro former u s s r former yugoslavia hawaiian trade zone east germany and west germany our united state energy mix and emission data wa obtained from the u s environmental protection agency egrid data for the year we used the state resource mix section for displaying the energy mix and the state output emission rate section for calculating emission in the united state we did not use the otherfossil data a the value were predominantly and in case in which the value wa nonzero it wa below a of july the most recent egrid data wa from the year we elected to use u s e i a data for consistency between the data source since the international data only contained an energy mix and no emission data we reverse engineered the formula used in the egrid data this give u additionally consistency between the separate datasets in case one wish to compare energy usage between different year of data we have included a script to allow for adding other year if you navigate to the package directory and go into the data folder you can use raw to json py first you need to download the u and international data in the year of your choice from the link above and place them in data raw year of the data after creating the required year folder then run the script with a flag for that year for example python raw to json py this will allow selecting that year when using package in the future by using the year optional argument for evaluate due to the method in which the energy measurement is being done through the intel rapl interface and nvidia smi our package is only available on linux kernel that have the rapl interface and or machine with an nvidia gpu a country s overall energy consumption mix is not necessarily representative of the mix of energy source used to produce electricity and even electricity production is not necessarily representative of electricity consumption due to import export however the e i a data is the most geographically comprehensive that we have found we are working on obtaining even more accurate data we would like to thank jon wilson for all his valuable insight with regard to the environmental aspect of our project

description: p tqdm make parallel processing with progress bar easy p tqdm is a wrapper around pathos multiprocessing and tqdm unlike python s default multiprocessing library pathos provides a more flexible parallel map which can apply almost any type of function including lambda function nested function and class method and can easily handle function with multiple argument tqdm is applied on top of pathos s parallel map and display a progress bar including an estimated time to completion pip install p tqdmlet s say you want to add two list element by element without any parallelism this can be done easily with a python map but if the list are much larger or the computation is more intense parallelism becomes a necessity however the syntax is often cumbersome p tqdm make it easy and add a progress bar too performs an ordered map in parallel return an iterator for an ordered map in parallel performs an unordered map in parallel return an iterator for an unordered map in parallel performs an ordered map sequentially return an iterator for an ordered map to be performed sequentially all p tqdm function accept any number of iterables a input a long a the number of iterables match the number of argument of the function to repeat a non iterable argument along with the iterables use python s partial from the functools library see the example below all the parallel p tqdm function can be passed the keyword num cpu to indicate how many cpu to use the default is all cpu num cpu can either be an integer to indicate the exact number of cpu to use or a float to indicate the proportion of cpu to use note that the parallel pool object used by p tqdm are automatically closed when the map finish processing all the parallel p tqdm function can be passed the keyword tqdm to choose a specific flavor of tqdm by default this value is taken from tqdm auto the tqdm parameter can be used pas p tqdm output to tqdm gui tqdm tk or any customized subclass of tqdm

description: a little package to convert a json into a table this project wa born out of a need to transform many jsons mined from apis to something that panda or a relational database could understand the difference between this package and json path package is that it designed to create table not just extract single value the package is available through pypi so simply go to your command line and you re also welcome to download the code from github and modify to suit your need and if you have time let me know what cool functionality you added and we can improve the project it work in a similar manner to json parsershere is a quick example to get you goingin this case you will get a table with two column and two row header and first row of data like these for more example refer to the test foldereach path you specify is a column in your final table each path that is setup is expanded according to the standard json path functionality this is for each path the converter start at the root of the json object and navigates each step a k a node of the path in order when it reach the final step in the path a k a leaf it output the resulting element of the json into the cell the final cell value is converted based on the standard json value a follows the intention behind stringifying the object array and boolean is to be able to pas the output to other data library e g panda or to a relational database with the exception of the final node array element are automatically expanded into row so for example a path a b applied to a json a b b would result into two row the array expansion functionality can be applied to the final node by explicitly using the operator a a final step e g a example result the reverse of this functionality not expand array if they are encountered before the end is not implemented only due to the lack of need since a path may result in multiple row there is the need to be able to combine the result of each column into the same table the joining mechanism is similar to an sql join where each cell row cell combination is matched to a row in the result using a matching value the matching value in this case is the last common element of the path this is best illustrated with an example the following table show the transformation applied to the sample json in the first case the type and number have a common path telephone and therefore the column are combined for the same telephone element if we then look at the name path it ha a common path contact with the rest of the column and therefore the value is repeated across the row in the second case the email and number only have a common path contact and since each path result in two row the only possible way to match these is to combine all the value resulting in row per contact total row since there are contact currently there are two operator supported and more operator will be implemented in later release both these change were made possible by changing the search method from depth first to breadth first a well a recursing through a tree rather than iterating through one column at a time in the wishlist we have i want to mention that whilst i inted to expand the functionality of this package at the moment it can only take a simple sequence of key to navigate a path this is the full functionality proposed by stefan gossner in his jsonpath is not yet implemented but we will get there if you are looking for a package that simply extract a single value from a json by using more complex path and it function i recommend you look at jsonpath rw by kenn knowles jsonpath ng by tomas aparicio or jsonpath by mark borkum i will continue to look for improvement in the package and hopefully add some useful functionality given the current popularity of the package the maintenance is in a best effort manner however if you have issue or bug to report let me know here and i will try my best to help you can use this package a you wish but unfortunatelly i cannot take responsibility of how this code is used or the result it provides it is up to you to test this doe what you want it to

description: this is a python implementation of the apted algorithm the state of the art solution for computing the tree edit distance which supersedes the rted algorithm it is a port of the original java implementation available at http github com databasegroup apted during the port some change were made to reduce the duplication on symmetric operation and to make it look more pythonic you can find more information about apted on the following website http tree edit distance dbresearch uni salzburg at if you want to refer to apted in a publication please cite and the source code is published under the mit licence found in the root directory of the project and in the header of each source file currently we support only the so called bracket notation for the input tree for example encoding a b x y f c corresponds to the following tree our tool computes two output tree edit distance value the minimum cost of transforming the source tree into the destination tree tree edit mapping a mapping between node that corresponds to the tree edit distance value node that are not mapped are deleted source tree or inserted destination tree this version were tested on python and first install it with pip if you want to compare the tree a b c and a b d please run the output is for more information on running option please runit is possible to customize the algorithm to run with custom tree with label different from simple string or custom data structure additionally it is possible to customize it to use a more sophisticated cost model than unit cost for customizing the algorithm you can create a custom config class by default the included config class consider tree with the atribute name a label and the atribute child a child in left to right preorder in addition to the config class we also provide a pereditoperationconfig class that allows you to specify weight for each operation if your main usage for apted is to obtain the mapping it is possible to configure the algorith to keep track of the mapping during the execution to do so we provide a function meta chained config that modifies existing config class note that this approach us much more memory and we didn t evaluate if it is faster than the original algorithm for the mapping with huge tree the execution time for the mapping test were about the same a the original algorithm feel free to submit pull resquests to this repository the codebase follows the pep convention however it is not too strict for instance it is okay to have line with a little more than character but try not to exceed too much please run python test py during your change to make sure everything is working it is also desirable to use coverage py to check test coverage coverage run test py mateusz pawliknikolaus augstenjoao felipe pimentelm pawlik and n augsten tree edit distance robust and memory efficient information system m pawlik and n augsten efficient computation of the tree edit distance acm transaction on database system tod m pawlik and n augsten rted a robust algorithm for the tree edit distance pvldb

description: qpd let you run the same sql select for now statement on different computing framework with panda like interface currently it support panda dask and ray via modin on ray qpd directly translates sql into panda like operation to run on the backend computing framework so it can be significantly faster than some other approach for example to dump panda dataframes into sqlite run sql and convert the result back into a panda dataframe however the top priority of qpd are correctness and consistency it ensures the result of implemented sql feature following sql convention and it ensures consistent behavior regardless of backend computing framework a typical case is groupby agg in panda or panda like framework if any of the group key is null the default behavior is to drop that group however in sql they are not dropped qpd follows the sql way qpd syntax is a subset of the intersection of spark sql and sqlite the correctness and consistency are extensively tested against sqlite practically spark sql and sqlite are highly consistent on both syntax and behavior so in other word qpd enables you to run common sqls and get the same result on panda sqlite spark dask ray and other backends that qpd will support in the future sql is one of the most important data processing language it is very scale agnostic and one of the major goal of the fugue project is to enrich sql and make sql platform agnostic qpd a a subproject of fugue focus on running sql on panda like framework it is an essential component to achieve the ultimate goal qpd can be installed from pypi if you want to use ray or dask a the backend you will need to install qpd with one of the target please read this to learn the best practice for initializing dask please read this to learn the best practice for initializing ray and read this for initializing modin ray please don t use dask a modin backend if you want to use qpd it s not testedby default qpd requires user to use upper cased keywords otherwise syntax error will be raised however if you really don t like this behavior you can turn it off the parameter is ignore case here is an example no that will not happen qpd is using spark sql syntax file spark sql is highly optimized if we create a koala backend correctness and consistency can be guaranteed but there will be no performance advantage so for spark please use spark sql if you use fugue sql on spark backend it will also directly use spark to run the sql statement we don t see the value to make qpd run on spark

description: this trampoline allows recursive function to recurse virtually or literally infinitely most existing recursive function can be converted with simple modification the implementation is tiny the gist of the module consists of a single function with around line of simple python code trampolined function are generator instead of recursing into other function directly they yield the generator of the call they want to recurse into the generator of the first call is invoked using the trampoline function this is easiest to understand with an example consider this simple recursive function this exhaust the stack when calling it with too large n compare this with our trampoline version we added a yield statement to the recursive call and wrapped the function call with trampoline trampoline take the generator created by the print number call and run it the generator then yield another generator of print number which then take over effectively recursing into it when a generator return the yielding generator take over again of course the trampolined function doesn t have to call itself any other trampolined function generator will do consider this recursive factorial again this exhaust the stack at our factorial call we now want to convert it for our trampoline but how do we get the result of the factorial call this us a rarely seen feature of yield it return value a an expression with this trampoline can send the result of the callee back to the caller here is the trampolined solution the function is suspended at the yield expression trampoline continues execution with the yielded generator and afterwards provides u with the returned value in the end trampoline return the value that wa returned by our first generator python requires that we add brace around a yield expression after a return making it look a little more ugly we can circumvent this by adding a variable in this case no extra brace are required exception are handled just a one might expect a seen in this example event tracebacks are preserved hiding no information in error case there is just one additional stack frame of the trampoline function for each generator yield this also mean that yield work just fine inside with block a trampolined function can raise tailcall which is an exception passing it the generator of the next function call this implementation us constant memory and theoretically work with any n until the result get too large beware that we still need to have a generator function so there ha to be a yield in the function reachable or not theidiom is recommended if the function doesn t yield any other call if you want to hide the trampolined ness of a function and simplify it usage expose a wrapper function that call the trampolined function with trampoline just make sure to always use the trampolined version from other trampolined function otherwise it will recurse a usual taking no advantage of the trampoline trampoline work just fine with method subclass can extend or override these trampolined method to provide their own implementation just make sure to always yield super call when extending a trampolined method lastly there are some downside to consider a we use yield for recursion we cannot use it to yield actual value simple case could be rewritten with a callback function or by appending or returning a list recursing hundred of thousand of time allocates a lot of object for local variable and for the generator themselves which all need to exist at the same time when overdoing it this can easily lead to multiple gigabyte on the stack of course if we mess up our exit condition and recurse infinitely we will exhaust our memory use tail call if they are an option otherwise an iterative approach may be preferable a said above when recursing extremely deeply the stack may get rather large these object not only have to be allocated but need to be freed a well when done which slows down the return path function call and exception handling overhead may come into play for function that don t recurse deeply or use a lot of tail call this should only matter for function that don t do a lot of work a simple tail calling count down from one million take about one second on a mediocre laptop when an exception occurs at ridiculous recursion depth displaying the traceback may take a while depending on the exception handler and formatter reducing sys tracebacklimit may help of course the traceback will then be cut off python s default traceback limit applies here too printing the last frame tail call don t have this problem a they don t appear in tracebacks

description: a schema and validator for yaml what s yaml see the current spec here and an introduction to the syntax here note some platform e g mac o may ship with only python and may not have pip installed installation of python should also install pip to preserve any system dependency on default software consider installing python a a local package please note replacing system provided python may disrupt other software mac o user may wish to investigate macports homebrew or building python from source in all three case apple s command line tool clt for xcode may be required see also developer below yamale can be run from the command line to validate one or many yaml file yamale will search the directory you supply current directory is default for yaml file each yaml file it find it will look in the same directory a that file for it schema if there is no schema yamale will keep looking up the directory tree until it find one if yamale can not find a schema it will tell you usage there are several way to feed yamale schema and data file the simplest way is to let yamale take care of reading and parsing your yaml file all you need to do is supply the file path you can pas a string of yaml to make schema and make data instead of passing a file path by using the content parameter if data is valid nothing will happen however if data is invalid yamale will throw a yamaleerror with a message containing all the invalid node and an array of validationresult you can also specify an optional parser if you d like to use the ruamel yaml yaml support instead to use yamale you must make a schema a schema is a valid yaml file with one or more document inside each node terminates in a string which contains valid yamale syntax for example str represents a string validator a basic schema and some yaml that validates take a look at the example section for more complex schema idea schema file may contain more than one yaml document node separated by the first document found will be the base schema any additional document will be treated a includes includes allow you to define a valid structure once and use it several time they also allow you to do recursion a schema with an include validator some valid yaml every root node not in the first yaml document will be treated like an include is equivalent to you can get recursion using the include validator this schema will validate this data after you construct a schema you can add extra external include definition by calling schema add include dict this method take a dictionary and add each key a another include by default yamale will provide error for extra element present in list and map that are not covered by the schema with strict mode disabled using the no strict command line option additional element will not cause any error in the api strict mode can be toggled by passing the strict true false flag to the validate function it is possible to mix strict and non strict mode by setting the strict true false flag in the include validator setting the option only for the included validators here are all the validators yamale know about every validator take a required keyword telling yamale whether or not that node must exist by default every node is required example str required false you can also require that an optional value is not none by using the none keyword by default yamale will accept none a a valid value for a key that s not required reject none value with none false in any validator example str required false none false some validators take keywords and some take argument some take both for instance the enum validator take one or more constant a argument and the required keyword enum a string false required false validates string example validates string against one or more regular expression example validates integer validates integer and float validates booleans validates null value validates from a list of constant example validates a date in the form of yyyy mm dd example validates a timestamp in the form of yyyy mm dd hh mm s example validates list if one or more validators are passed to list only node that pas at least one of those validators will be accepted example validates map use when you want a node to contain freeform data similar to list map take one or more validators to run against the value of it node and only node that pas at least one of those validators will be accepted by default only the value of node are validated and the key aren t checked example validates ipv and ipv address example validates mac address example validates against a union of type use when a node must contain one and only one of several type it is valid if at least one of the listed validators is valid if no validators are given accept any value example validates against a subset of type unlike the any validator this validators allows one or more of several type a such it automatically validates against a list it is valid if all value can be validated against at least one validator example validates included structure must supply the name of a valid include example it is also possible to add your own custom validators this is an advanced topic but here is an example of adding a date validator and using it in a schema a date to validate yaml file when you run your program s test use yamale s yamaletestcaseexample base dir string path to prepend to all other path this is optional schema string of path to the schema file to use one schema file per test case yaml string or list of yaml file to validate accepts glob yamale us tox to run it test against multiple python version to run test first checkout yamale install tox then run make test in yamale s root directory you may also have to install the correct python version to test with a well note on python version tox ini specifies the lowest and highest version of python supported by yamale unless your development environment is configured to support testing against multiple python version one or more of the test branch may fail one method of enabling testing against multiple version of python is to install pyenv and tox pyenv and to use pyenv install and pyenv local to ensure that tox is able to locate appropriate python yamale us github action to upload new tag to pypi to release a new version github action will take care of the rest

description: the reproject package is a python package to reproject astronomical image using various technique via a uniform interface by reprojection we mean the re gridding of image from one world coordinate system to another for example changing the pixel resolution orientation coordinate system currently we have implemented reprojection of celestial image by interpolation like swarp by the adaptive and anti aliased algorithm of deforest and by finding the exact overlap between pixel on the celestial sphere like montage it can also reproject to from healpix projection by relying on the astropy healpix package for more information including on how to install the package see http reproject readthedocs io

description: locket implement a file based lock that can be used by multiple process provided they use the same path lock largely behave a non reentrant lock instance from the threading module in the standard library specifically their behaviour is lock are uniquely identified by the file being locked both in the same process and across different process lock are either in a locked or unlocked state when the lock is unlocked calling acquire return immediately and change the lock state to locked when the lock is locked calling acquire will block until the lock state change to unlocked or until the timeout expires if a process hold a lock any thread in that process can call release to change the state to unlocked calling release on an unlocked lock raise lockerror behaviour of lock after fork is undefined

description: this package provides a set of corruption that can be applied to image in order to benchmark the robustness of neural network these corruption are not meant to be used a training data augmentation but rather to test the network against unseen perturbation for more information have a look at the paper on the original corruption package by hendrycks and dietterich benchmarking neural network robustness to common corruption and surface variation this package is pip installable via pip install imagecorruptions an example of how to use the corruption function is given below looping over all available corruption can be done either by name or by index note that the first image corruption are the common corruption the one you get via get corruption name if you really wish to use these a data augmentation there exist four additional validation corruption which can be accessed via get corruption name validation which should then be used to test the corruption robustness of the trained model if you use our code or the imagecorruptions package please consider citing this package is an extension of the image corruption function provided by dan hendrycks in the repository corruption the image corruption implemented by hendrycks are generalized to work on image with arbitrary image dimension and aspect ratio aswell a on grayscale image we furthermore removed the dependency to libmagickwand and the python api wand and reimplemented the motion blur in python

description: install in the usual manner from pypi or from the downloaded source code directory the load repertoire write repertoire and validate repertoire function have been deprecated for the new generic load airr data write airr data and validate airr data function these new function are backwards compatible with the repertoire metadata format but also support the new airr object such a germlineset repertoiregroup genotypeset cell and clone this new format is defined by the datafile schema which describes a standard set of object included in a file containing airr data model presentation currently the airr datafile doe not completely support rearrangement so user should continue using airr tsv file and it specific function also the repertoire template function ha been deprecated for the schema template method which can now be called on any airr schema to create a blank object the airr package contains function to read and write airr data model file the file format is either yaml or json and the package provides a light wrapper over the standard parser the file need a json yaml or yml file extension so that the proper parser is utilized all of the airr object are loaded into memory at once and no streaming interface is provided why are the airr object such a repertoire germlineset and etc in a list versus in a dictionary keyed by their identifier e g repertoire id there are two primary reason for this first the identifier might not have been assigned yet some system might allow miairr metadata to be entered but the identifier is assigned to that data later by another process without the identifier the data could not be stored in a dictionary secondly the list allows the data to have a default ordering if you know that the data ha a unique identifier then you can quickly create a dictionary object using a comprehension for example with repertoire another example with germline set writing an airr data file is also a light wrapper over standard yaml or json parser multiple airr object such a repertoire germlineset and etc can be written together into the same file in this example we use the airr library template method to create some blank repertoire object and write them to a file a with the read function the complete list of repertoire are written at once there is no streaming interface the airr package contains function to read and write airr rearrangement tsv file a either iterables or panda data frame the usage is straightforward a the file format is a typical tab delimited file but the package performs some additional validation and type conversion beyond using a standard csv reader similar to the read operation write function are provided for either creating a writer class to perform row wise output or writing the entire content of a panda data frame to a file again usage is straightforward with the airr output function simply performing some type conversion and field ordering operation by default create rearrangement will only write the required field in the output file additional field can be included in the output file by providing the field parameter with an array of additional field name a common operation is to read an airr rearrangement file and then write an airr rearrangement file with additional field in it while keeping all of the existing field from the original file the derive description: this is not the timeout you are looking for warningplease read this readme carefully and only use this plugin if you understand the consequence remember your test suite need to be fast timeouts are a last resort not an expected failure mode this plugin will time each test and terminate it when it take too long termination may or may not be graceful please see below but when aborting it will show a stack dump of all thread running at the time this is useful when running test under a continuous integration server or simply if you don t know why the test suite hang notewhile by default on posix system pytest will continue to execute the test after a test ha timed out this is not always possible often the only sure way to interrupt a hanging test is by terminating the entire process a this is a hard termination o exit it will result in no teardown junit xml output etc but the plugin will ensure you will have the debugging output on stderr nevertheless which is the most important part at this stage see below for detailed information on the timeout method and their side effect the pytest timeout plugin ha been tested on python and higher including pypy see tox ini for currently tested version install is a simple a e g now you can run the test suite while setting a timeout in second any individual test which take longer than the given duration will be terminated furthermore you can also use a decorator to set the timeout for an individual test if combined with the timeout flag this will override the timeout for this individual test by default the plugin will not time out any test you must specify a valid timeout for the plugin to interrupt long running test a timeout is always specified a a number of second and can be defined in a number of way from low to high priority you can set a global timeout in the pytest configuration file using the timeout option e g the pytest timeout environment variable set a global timeout overriding a possible value in the configuration file the timeout command line option set a global timeout overriding both the environment variable and configuration option using the timeout marker on test item you can specify timeouts on a per item basis setting a timeout to second disables the timeout so if you have a global timeout set you can still disable the timeout by using the mark interrupting test which hang is not always a simple and can be platform dependent furthermore some method of terminating a test might conflict with the code under test itself the pytest timeout plugin try to pick the most suitable method based on your platform but occasionally you may need to specify a specific timeout method explicitly if a timeout method doe not work your safest bet is to use the thread method this is the surest and most portable method it is also the default on system not supporting the signal method for each test item the pytest timeout plugin start a timer thread which will terminate the whole process after the specified timeout when a test item finish this timer thread is cancelled and the test run continues the downside of this method are that there is a relatively large overhead for running each test and that test run are not completed this mean that other pytest feature like e g junit xml output or fixture teardown will not function normally the second issue might be alleviated by using the boxed option of the pytest xdist plugin the benefit of this method is that it will always work furthermore it will still provide you debugging information by printing the stack of all the thread in the application to stderr if the system support the sigalrm signal the signal method will be used by default this method schedule an alarm when the test item start and cancel the alarm when the test finish if the alarm expires during the test the signal handler will dump the stack of any other thread running to stderr and use pytest fail to interrupt the test the benefit of this method is that the pytest process is not terminated and the test run can complete normally the main issue to look out for with this method is that it may interfere with the code under test if the code under test us sigalrm itself thing will go wrong and you will have to choose the thread method the timeout method can be specified by using the timeout method option in the pytest configuration file the timeout method command line parameter or the timeout marker simply set their value to the string thread or signal to override the default method on a marker this is done using the method keyword the full signature of the timeout marker is you can use either positional or keyword argument for both the timeout and the method neither need to be present see the marker api documentation and example for the various way marker can be applied to test item the plugin will happily terminate timeouts in the finalisers of fixture the timeout specified applies to the entire process of setting up fixture running the test and finalising the fixture however when a timeout occurs in a fixture finaliser and the test suite continues i e the signal method is used it must be realised that subsequent fixture which need to be finalised might not have been executed which could result in a broken test suite anyway in case of doubt the thread method which terminates the entire process might result in clearer output the timeout applies to the entire test including any fixture which may need to be setup or torn down for the test the exact affected fixture depends on which scope they are and whether other test will still use the same fixture if the timeouts really are too short to include fixture duration firstly make the timeouts larger if this really isn t an option a timeout func only boolean setting exists which can be set in the pytest ini configuration file a documented in pytest help this plugin try to avoid triggering the timeout when a debugger is detected this is mostly a convenience so you do not need to remember to disable the timeout when interactively debugging the way this plugin detects whether or not a debugging session is active is by checking if a trace function is set and if one is it check to see if the module it belongs to is present in a set of known debugging framework module or if pytest itself drop you into a pdb session using pdb or similar pytest timeout provides two hook that can be used for extending the tool these hook are used for for setting the timeout timer and cancelling it it the timeout is not reached for example pytest asyncio can provide asyncio specific code that generates better traceback and point on timed out await instead of the running loop ieration see pytest hook documentation for more info regarding to use description: rlax pronounced relax is a library built on top of jax that expose useful building block for implementing reinforcement learning agent full documentation can be found at rlax readthedocs io you can install the latest released version of rlax from pypi via or you can install the latest development version from github all rlax code may then be just in time compiled for different hardware e g cpu gpu tpu using jax jit in order to run the example you will also need to clone the repo and install the additional requirement optax haiku and bsuite the operation and function provided are not complete algorithm but implementation of reinforcement learning specific mathematical operation that are needed when building fully functional agent capable of learning the library support both on policy and off policy learning i e learning from data sampled from a policy different from the agent s policy see file level and function level doc string for the documentation of the reward the behaviour of the agent is characterized by a probability distribution over action conditioned on past observation of the environment the policy the agent seek a policy that from any given step maximises the discounted cumulative reward that will be collected from that point onwards the return often the agent policy or the environment dynamic itself are stochastic in this case the description: reverb is an efficient and easy to use data storage and transport system designed for machine learning research reverb is primarily used a an experience replay system for distributed reinforcement learning algorithm but the system also support multiple data structure representation such a fifo lifo and priority queue please keep in mind that reverb is not hardened for production use and while we do our best to keep thing in working order thing may break or segfault warning reverb currently only support linux based os the recommended way to install reverb is with pip we also provide instruction to build from source using the same docker image we use for release tensorflow can be installed separately or a part of the pip install installing tensorflow a part of the install ensures compatibility starting with version debug build of reverb are uploaded to google cloud storage the build can be downloaded or installed directly via pip following the pattern below gsutils can be used to navigate the directory structure to ensure the file are there e g gsutil l g rl infra build dm reverb build dbg to build your own debug binary see the build instruction for python for python and follow this pattern this guide detail how to build reverb from source starting a reverb server is a simple a create a client to communicate with the server write some data to the table an item can also reference multiple data element the item we have added to reverb can be read by sampling them continue with the reverb tutorial for an interactive tutorial experience replay ha become an important tool for training off policy reinforcement learning policy it is used by algorithm such a deep q network dqn soft actor critic sac deep deterministic policy gradient ddpg and hindsight experience replay however building an efficient easy to use and scalable replay system can be challenging for good performance reverb is implemented in c and to enable distributed usage it provides a grpc service for adding sampling and updating the content of the table python client expose the full functionality of the service in an easy to use fashion furthermore native tensorflow ops are available for performant integration with tensorflow and tf data although originally designed for off policy reinforcement learning reverb s flexibility make it just a useful for on policy reinforcement or even un supervised learning creative user have even used reverb to store and distribute frequently updated data such a model weight acting a an in memory light weight alternative to a distributed file system where each table represents a file a reverb server consists of one or more table a table hold item and each item reference one or more data element table also define sample and removal selection strategy a maximum item capacity and a rate limiter multiple item can reference the same data element even if these item exist in different table this is because item only contain reference to data element a opposed to a copy of the data itself this also mean that a data element is only removed when there exists no item that contains a reference to it for example it is possible to set up one table a a prioritized experience replay per for transition sequence of length and another table a a fifo queue of sequence of length in this case the per data could be used to train dqn and the fifo data to train a transition model for the environment item are automatically removed from the table when one of two condition are met inserting a new item would cause the number of item in the table to exceed it maximum capacity table s removal strategy is used to determine which item to remove an item ha been sampled more than the maximum number of time permitted by the table s rate limiter such item is deleted data element not referenced anymore by any item are also deleted user have full control over how data is sampled and removed from reverb table the behavior is primarily controlled by the item selection strategy provided to the table a the sampler and remover in combination with the rate limiter and max time sampled a wide range of behavior can be achieved some commonly used configuration include uniform experience replaya set of n most recently inserted item are maintained by setting sampler reverb selector uniform the probability to select an item is the same for all item due to reverb rate limiter minsize sampling request will block until item have been inserted by setting remover reverb selector fifo when an item need to be removed the oldest item is removed first example of algorithm that make use of uniform experience replay include sac and ddpg prioritized experience replaya set of n most recently inserted item by setting sampler reverb selector prioritized priority exponent the probability to select an item is proportional to the item s priority note see schaul tom et al for the algorithm used in this implementation of prioritized experience replay example of algorithm that make use of prioritized experience replay are dqn and it variant and distributed distributional deterministic policy gradient queuecollection of up to n item where the oldest item is selected and removed in the same operation if the collection contains item then insert call are blocked until it is no longer full if the collection is empty then sample call are blocked until there is at least one item example of algorithm that make use of queue are impala and asynchronous implementation of proximal policy optimization reverb defines several selector that can be used for item sampling or removal any of these strategy can be used for sampling or removing item from a table this give user the flexibility to create customized table that best fit their need rate limiter allow user to enforce condition on when item can be inserted and or sampled from a table here is a list of the rate limiter that are currently available in reverb reverb server are unaware of each other and when scaling up a system to a multi server setup data is not replicated across more than one node this make reverb unsuitable a a traditional database but ha the benefit of making it trivial to scale up system where some level of data loss is acceptable distributed system can be horizontally scaled by simply increasing the number of reverb server when used in combination with a grpc compatible load balancer the address of the load balanced target can simply be provided to a reverb client and operation will automatically be distributed across the different node you ll find detail about the specific behavior in the documentation of the relevant method and class if a load balancer is not available in your setup or if more control is required then system can still be scaled in almost the same way simply increase the number of reverb server and create separate client for each server reverb support checkpointing the state and content of reverb server can be stored to permanent storage while pointing the server serializes all of it data and metadata needed to reconstruct it during this process the server block all incoming insert sample update and delete request checkpointing is done with a call from the reverb client to restore the reverb server from a checkpoint refer to tfrecord checkpointer h for detail on the implementation of checkpointing in reverb installing dm reverb using pip will install a reverb server script which accepts it config a a textproto for example the rate limiter config is equivalent to the python expression minsize see rate limiter py if you use this code please cite the reverb paper a

description: launchpad is a library that simplifies writing distributed program by seamlessly launching them on a variety of different platform switching between local and distributed execution requires only a flag change launchpad introduces a programming model that represents a distributed system a a graph data structure a program describing the system s topology each node in the program graph represents a service in the distributed system i e the fundamental unit of computation that we are interested in running a node are added to this graph launchpad construct a handle for each of them a handle ultimately represents a client to the yet to be constructed service a directed edge in the program graph representing communication between two service is created when the handle associated with one node is given to another at construction time this edge originates from the receiving node indicating that the receiving node will be the one initiating communication this process allows launchpad to define cross service communication simply by passing handle to node launchpad provides a number of node type including using launchpad involves writing node and defining the topology of your distributed program by passing to each node reference of the other node that it can communicate with the core data structure dealing with this is called a launchpad program which can then be executed seamlessly with a number of supported runtimes launchpad support a number of launch type both for running program on a single machine in a distributed manner or in a form of a test launch type can be controlled by the launch type argument passed to lp launch method or specified through the lp launch type command line flag please refer to the documentation of the launchtype for detail please keep in mind that launchpad is not hardened for production use and while we do our best to keep thing in working order thing may break or segfault warning launchpad currently only support linux based os the recommended way to install launchpad is with pip we also provide instruction to build from source using the same docker image we use for release tensorflow can be installed separately or a part of the pip install installing tensorflow a part of the install ensures compatibility similarily reverb can be installed ensuring compatibility the most convenient way to develop launchpad is with docker this way you can compile and test launchpad inside a container without having to install anything on your host machine while you can still use your editor of choice for making code change the step are a follows checkout launchpad s source code from github build the docker container to be used for compiling and testing launchpad you can specify tensorflow pip parameter to set the version of tensorflow to build against you can also specify which version s of python container should support the command below enables support for python and the next step is to enter the built docker image binding checked out launchpad s source to tmp launchpad within the container at this point you can build and install launchpad within the container by executing by default it build python version you can change that with python flag to make sure installation wa successful and launchpad work a expected you can run some example provided to make change to launchpad codebase edit source checked out from github directly on your host machine outside of the docker container all change are visible inside the docker container to recompile just run the os build sh script again from the docker container in order to reduce compilation time of the consecutive run make sure to not exit the docker container if you use launchpad in your work please cite the accompanying technical report we greatly appreciate all the help from reverb and tf agent team in setting up building and testing setup for launchpad

description: a robust hyperparameter tuner for high dimensional categorically and or conditionally parameterized intractable optimization problem ex neural network neural network hyper parameter optimization is an especially challenging task due to a few different reason parameter can be highly codependent adjusting a single parameter may not be enough to get over a saddle point you will likely have to adjust many parameter simultaneously to escape local minimum you may have scenario where adjusting a parameter can completely alter the performance of other parameter a well making it very difficult to sample historically better value more often and run the risk of sampling value based on the modeling of a suboptimal parameter space attempting to model which parameter are more likely to be better will also require a lot of trial to overcome this level of variance noise even then a alluded to above the best parameter value on average will not always be the best parameter value overall the search space can be highly non convex with many categorical discrete valued conditional and nested parameter this sort of parameter space make it very difficult to generate any sort of quantitative probability model for high end performance where local minimum is not good enough and we want the best possible performance or for domain where there ha not been extensive research and there is not a general understanding on what type of choice work better than others we might want to tune many parameter at once and the dimensionality of the search space can get very large such that bayesian optimization related method are not very effective recent research ha discussed there is not a lot of reproducible evidence that show any of today s state of the art technique significantly beat a plain old random search with some form of early stopping http arxiv org pdf pdfall of the issue mentioned above make it very difficult if not impossible to do any sort of intelligently guided search for nn architecture training hyperparameters that is why this tuner opts against attempting to build some sort of surrogate function or gradient based method to model the probability of the search space and instead aim for something simpler and hopefully more robust to the problem we re facing the user shouldn t expect a magic algorithm that take the least amount of step possible to reach global minimum but they should be able to expect something that beat brute force random search for almost all use case by a respectable margin which is really what nn tuning need at this stage the storm tuner can be thought of intuitively a a combination of a grid search combined with random search where the distance between the current best configuration and the next evaluation candidate is probability based we randomly mutate the current best configuration along different ax and sometimes even multiple time along the same axis the number of mutation made for the next evaluation candidate is based on a user defined probability the default value for randomize axis factor is which mean that there is a chance just one mutation will be made there is a chance two mutation will be made a chance that three mutation will be made and so on this approach aim to address the issue stated above by allowing enough freedom so that we do respect the non convexity of the search space and co dependency of variable while also probabilistically restricting how different the next evaluation candidate is from the current best to provide some level of guidance and locality to the search pip install storm tunerhere we define our hyperparameter space by providing our own configuration building method note the configuration building method is an important component of storm s functionality even though parameter can be accessed elsewhere for example when the model is trained or during data preprocessing all parameter must be defined in this method this is because storm will execute this function in the background prior to the user defined execution of a trial the reason for this is that storm will flag parameter that are actually drawn from and then create a hash of this particular configuration this is a vital component a it ensures we never waste resource testing virtually identical configuration after we define our hp space it will usually make the most sense for our function to return an untrained model at this point however one may opt to return more than a model in some circumstance for example an optimizer or they may even opt to not return anything at all and build the model later this is entirely up to the user all parameter take the form hp param parameter name value value ordered false setting a parameter to ordered true will ensure the tuner is only able to select adjacent value per a single mutation step this is an important feature for parameter where there is ordinality we are required to override the run trial method for our own tuner implementation this encapsulates all the execution of a single trial all the run trial method need to do is assign a score to the trial self score trial trial score using a given parameter configuration trial hyperparameters how the user generates a score for the configuration is entirely at their discretion the self build fn hp function called in run trial is what will supply u with a blank model a mentioned above a we can see any argument you provide in the search entry method can be accessed in your run trial method this is also true for build model a well if any parameter need to be passed in at this scope we initialize our tuner and provide our training dataone of the main goal of this library is to save the user from having to tune the tuner itself an excess of tunable variable can confuse the user make intuitive documentation more difficult and even have a substantial negative effect on the tuner s performance if they are not set correctly with this tuner we have main adjustable parameter to customize your search preference init random how many initial iteration to perform random search for this is helpful for getting the search to an average decent configuration so that we don t waste too much time descending from a suboptimal starting point randomize axis factor the main exploitative explorative tradeoff parameter a value closer to mean that step will generally have more mutation a value closer to will mean step are more likely to only do a single mutation a value of seems reasonable in most case and will almost always be good enough for both of these parameter the higher degree of parameter codependency that is expected and or the more parameter that you are optimizing it may be beneficial to set these value higher ex initial random iteration and or randomize acis factor the storm tuner is designed to be a simple a possible the tuner supply a parameter configuration and the user assigns this configuration a score we leave it up to the user to implement any number of methodology that might fit their goal and use case these can include storm should be designed to be a generic a possible and there is actually nothing specific to neural network or a particular nn library coded in this project this type of freedom also allows the user to optimize parameter used at various stage of the experiment a well ex data pre processing model architecture and training because of the tuner s experiment agnostic approach storm can be even more advantageous when used with various branch of ml that utilize nns for the model yet have another set of hyper parameter to optimize that can make the search space even trickier and harder for traditional approach to handle for example reinforcement learning of course most of the success of storm revolves around the user s ability to parameterize the search space appropriately storm will only be a good a the parameter space it operates on a few thing to keep in mind when parameterizing your search space in most case the selection of value should be fairly intuitive batch size momentum kernel size lr e e e at the end of the day there is then nothing stopping the user from re parameterizing their search space after narrowing in on promising area from running storm tuner at a broader scope although the example here use tensorflow kera storm work with any library or algorithm sklearn pytorch etc one simply defines any parameter we are optimizing in build fn the user can decide to return a model right here and utilize storm s inline parameterization or they can opt to use parameter in run trial storm should be used for optimization problem where the parameter space can be high dimensional and ha many categorical conditional variable storm should also be used when parameter do not need to be optimized at very fine level but rather we need to find good general choice in short storm will be most effective when there are many codependent decision to be made storm will probably not be the best tuner to use if you are optimizing many real valued parameter that always have an affect on the target function with low codependencies and which can be sensitive to small change such that we should offer the real valued spectrum of value and not just a few bin to chose from for these type of problem bayesian optimization will still be more effective a storm trial like the one used in the run trial method above ha a metric dictionary to easily allows u to store any pertinent information to this trial for review later on run compare to random search py from example directory to compare performance to random search for yourself here we can see that over ten trial each storm ha a clear advantage tuned score mean stdev random score mean stdev run compare to optuna py from example directory to compare performance to a state of the art optimizer like optuna here we can see that with tuning iteration and trial per each tuner storm ha a slight edge and is definitely competitive storm score mean std optuna score mean std

description: the verboselogs package extends python s logging module to add the log level notice spam success and verbose the notice level sits between the predefined warning and info level the spam level sits between the predefined debug and notset level the success level sits between the predefined warning and error level the verbose level sits between the predefined info and debug level the code to do this is simple and short but i still don t want to copy paste it to every project i m working on hence this package it s currently tested on python and pypy installationusagepylint pluginoverview of logging levelscontactlicensethe verboselogs package is available on pypi which mean installation should be a simple a there s actually a multitude of way to install python package e g the per user site package directory virtual environment or just installing system wide and i have no intention of getting into that discussion here so if this intimidates you then read up on your option before returning to these instruction it s very simple to start using the verboselogs package here s a skeleton of a very simple python program with a command line interface and configurable logging if you want to set verboselogger a the default logging class for all subsequent logger instance you can do so using verboselogs install if using the above verboselogs install approach pylint is not smart enough to recognize that logging is using verboselogs resulting in error like to fix this verboselogs provides a pylint plugin verboselogs pylint which when loaded with pylint load plugins verboselogs pylint add the verboselogs method and constant to pylint s understanding of the logging module the table below show the name numeric value and description of the predefined log level and the verbose notice and spam level defined by this package plus some note that i added levelvaluedescriptionnotesnotset when a logger is created the level is set to notset note that the root logger is created with level warning this level isn t intended to be used explicitly however when a logger ha it level set to notset it effective level will be inherited from the parent logger spam way too verbose for regular debugging but nice to have when someone is getting desperate in a late night debugging session and decides that they want a much instrumentation a possible debug detailed information typically of interest only when diagnosing problem usually at this level the logging output is so low level that it s not useful to user who are not familiar with the software s internals verbose detailed information that should be understandable to experienced user to provide insight in the software s behavior a sort of high level debugging information info confirmation that thing are working a expected notice auditing information about thing that have multiple success path or may need to be reverted warning an indication that something unexpected happened or indicative of some problem in the near future e g disk space low the software is still working a expected success a very explicit confirmation of success error due to a more serious problem the software ha not been able to perform some function critical a serious error indicating that the program itself may be unable to continue running the latest version of verboselogs is available on pypi and github the documentation is hosted on read the doc for bug report please create an issue on github if you have question suggestion etc feel free to send me an e mail at peter peterodding com this software is licensed under the mit license peter odding

portable network graphic png portable anymaps pnm etc portable arbitrary map pam adobe postscript and adobe photoshop document making the use of other graphic package obselete in these case but description: description installation usage license rapidfuzz is a fast string matching library for python and c which is using the string similarity calculation from fuzzywuzzy however there are a couple of aspect that set rapidfuzz apart from fuzzywuzzy there are several way to install rapidfuzz the recommended method are to either use pip the python package manager or conda an open source cross platform package manager rapidfuzz can be installed with pip the following way there are pre built binary wheel of rapidfuzz for macos and later linux x and window wheel for armv l raspberry pi zero and armv l raspberry pi are available on piwheels heavy multiplication x failure importerror dll load failed if you run into this error on window the reason is most likely that the visual c redistributable is not installed which is required to find c library the c version includes the and version rapidfuzz can be installed with conda rapidfuzz can be installed directly from the source distribution by cloning the repository this requires a c capable compiler some simple function are shown below a complete documentation of all function can be found here scorer in rapidfuzz can be found in the module fuzz and string metric the process module make it compare string to list of string this is generally more performant than using the scorer directly from python here are some example on the usage of processor in rapidfuzz the full documentation of processor can be found herethe following benchmark give a quick performance comparison between rapidfuzz and fuzzywuzzy more detailed benchmark for the string metric can be found in the documentation for this simple comparison i generated a list of string with length that is compared to a sample of element from this list the first benchmark compare the performance of the scorer in fuzzywuzzy and rapidfuzz when they are used directly from python in the following way the following graph show how many element are processed per second with each of the scorer there are big performance difference between the different scorer however each of the scorer is faster in rapidfuzzthe second benchmark compare the performance when the scorer are used in combination with cdist in the following way the following graph show how many element are processed per second with each of the scorer in rapidfuzz the usage of scorer through processor like cdist is a lot faster than directly using it that s why they should be used whenever possible if you are using rapidfuzz for your work and feel like giving a bit of your own benefit back to support the project consider sending u money through github sponsor or paypal that we can use to buy u free time for the maintenance of this great library to fix bug in the software review and integrate code contribution to improve it feature and documentation or to just take a deep breath and have a cup of tea every once in a while thank you for your support support the project through github sponsor or via paypal rapidfuzz is licensed under the mit license since i believe that everyone should be able to use it without being forced to adopt the gpl license that s why the library is based on an older version of fuzzywuzzy that wa mit licensed a well this old version of fuzzywuzzy can be found here

description: a fast algorithm to optimally compose privacy guarantee of differentially private dp algorithm to arbitrary accuracy our method is based on the notion of privacy loss random variable to quantify the privacy loss of dp algorithm for more detail see currently the following mechanism are supported which computes the privacy curve delta left mathcal n sigma p mathcal n sigma p mathcal n sigma right where p is the sampling probability and sigma is the noise multiplier the second argument represents a mixture distribution which computes the privacy curve delta left mathcal n sigma mathcal n sigma right where sigma is the noise multiplier which computes the privacy curve delta left textsf lap textsf lap mu right it is also possible to compose dp guarantee directlyit is also possible to add custom mechanism for the composition computation an example can be found in this notebook all we need is to implement the cdf of the privacy loss distribution it is possible to compose different mechanism the following example will compute the composition of three different mechanism m a m b and m c composed with themselves m n and o time respectively an application for such a composition is dp sgd training with increasing batch size and therefore increasing sampling probability after m n o training step the resulting privacy mechanism m for the whole training process is given by m m a circ dot circ m m a circ m b circ dot circ m n b circ m c circ dot circ m o c using the prv accountant we need to create a privacy random variable for each mechanismnext we need to create an accountant instance the accountant will take care of most of the numerical intricacy such a finding the support of the prv and discretisation in order to find a suitable domain the accountant need to know about the largest number of composition of each prv with itself that will be computed larger value of max self composition lead to larger domain which can cause slower performance in the case of dp sgd a reasonable choice of max self composition would be the total number of training step additionally the desired error bound for varepsilon and delta are required aliased resizing and surprising subtlety in gan evaluation gaurav parmar richard zhang jun yan zhu cvpr cmu and adobeif you find this repository useful for your research please cite the following work aliased resizing operation the definition of resizing function are mathematical and should never be a function of the library being used unfortunately implementation differ across commonly used library they are often implemented incorrectly by popular library try out the different resizing implementation in the google colab notebook here the inconsistency among implementation can have a drastic effect of the evaluation metric the table below show that ffhq dataset image resized with bicubic implementation from other library opencv pytorch tensorflow opencv have a large fid score when description: globally scoped configuration with argparse integration first define a class that extends effortless config config and specify your default configuration value inside it then you can example py and finish it off with we can see the available setting with h help we can then override configuration setting from the command line list and dict type setting can be overridden by passing json string from the command line e g configuration group are family of setting that you want to tie together for example you might have some machine learning problem for which you have a large model and a small model and you want to easily switch between the two model without having to specify all parameter on the command line every time to specify group use the setting function setting ha the signature where t is union int float str bool list dict nonetype and kwargs is a map from group name to value specifying parameter by value is shorthand for a setting with no group i e some key value is equivalent to some key setting default value when using group you must first define the group name using the config group list then in your code you can use these setting like in the basic examplenow we see an additional configuration option when we ask for help the configuration option specifies the configuration group and default to default if omitted for example we can also override individual setting in conjunction with group individual setting take precedence over the group setting when writing test you can use the config override context manager to override individual setting the config override method can also be used without context management in conjunction with config reset to default btw this ha nothing to do with chef s effortless config project i forgot to google
